mber. 1930.\nBYRON S. ADAMS. FEDERAL-AMERICAN\nNATIONAL BANK AND TRUST CO., by\nWM. C JOHNSON, vice pres iSeal.i At\ntest: VICTOR S MERSCH. Deputy Register\nof Wills for the District of Columbia. Clerk\nof the Probate Court. de6.13.20\nBARNARD Jl JOHNSON, Attorneys.\nIN THE SUPREME COURT OF THE Dis\ntrict of Columbia.\u2014Godwin Ordway et al.,\nplaintiffs, vs. Charles Glover. Walter Smith.\nRichard S. Cox. John A. Smith, trustee, and\n\u25a0William Hunter, jr.. trustee, if living, and\nIf dead their unknown hens, alienees and\ndevisees. defendants. \u2014Equity No. 520a4.\nOrder of Publication.\u2014The cbiect of this\nsuit is to declare the title to the following\ndescribed real estate and premises, situate.\nl*-ing and being in the District of Columbia,\nto wit: Part of square south of square\nsouth of square 1296. described as follow's:\nB*cinning for the same at a point on the\nvest line of Thirty-fifth street distant 60\nfeet north from the intersection of the west\nline of said Thirty-fifth street wtih the\nnorth line of R street, and running, thence\nnorth along .said west line of Thlrty-fi.th\nstreet 136 feet, more or less, to the south\nwest coiner of the land conveyed to Peter\nDoutv by John Threlkeld by deed recorded\nin Liber W. B 1, folio 252. of the land rec\nords of the District of Columbia: thence\n\u25a0west with the said Doutys south line 1-0\nfeet thence south and parallel to said\nThirtv-fifth street 136 feet, more or less, to\nthe southwest corner of the land conveyed\nto George Fenwick by said John Thre.keld\ndeed recorded in Liber E. folio 12 1, of\nsaid land records; thence east along the\nsouth line of the land conveyed to said\nFenwick 120 feet to the wen line of Thirty\nfifth street and the place cf beginning: the\nabove-described land being designated on\nthe books of the assessor of the Dtstric. of\nColumbia for taxation purposes as lot B in\nsquare south of square south of square\n1295: to be complete in fee simple by ad\nverse pors-ssion for the requisite numher of\nwears by said plaintiffs and their predeces\nsors in title, and enjoining the defendants\nfrom thereafter asserting any alleged right,\ntitle or claim thereto. Upon motion of the\nplaintiff, it is by the court this fourth day\nof December. 1930. ordered that the De\nfendants herein. Charles Glover. Val.rr\nSmith. Richard S. Cox. John A. Smith, trus\ntee. and William Hunter. Jr., trustee, if\nliving, and if dead their unknown heirs,\n\u25a0lienees and devisees, cause their appear\nance to be entered herein on or before the\nfirst rule day occurring after the expiration\nof three months from the day of tne first\npublication of this order, otherwise this\ncause will be proceeded with as in case of\ndefault, provided a copy of this order be\npublished twice a month for three months\nin the Washington Law Reporter and Eve\nning Star newspaper before said date.\nJESSE C. ADKINS. Justice. A true copy.\nTslalJ Test: FRANK E. CUNNINGHAM,\nClerk. By HARRY M. HULL, Asst. Clerk.\nde6.20 je3.13.fc3.14\nRAYMOND B. DICKEY, Attorney.\nSUPREME COURT OF THE DISTRICT OF\nColumbia. Holding Probate Court. \u2014No.\n41126. Administration\u2014This is to give no\ntice that the subscriber, of the District of\nColumbia, has obtained from the Piobaie\nCourt of the District cf Columbia, letters\ntestamentary on the estate of Ehsabt h A.\nKosafy, late of the District of Columbia, de\nceased. All persons having claims against\nthe deceased are hereby warned to exhibit\nthe same, with the vouchers thereof, legally\nAuthenticated, to the subscriber, on or be\nfore the 28th day of November. AD. 1931;\notherwise they may by law be-excluded from\nall benefit of said estate. Given unaer my\nhand thig 28th day of November. 1930.\nLOUIS A P.OSAFY. 2652 Wood lev pi nw.\nSeal, i Attest THEODORE COGSWELL.\nRegister of Wills for the District of Colum\nbla- Clerk of the Probate Court. de6.13.20\nAMBROSE L. GRINDLEY. SS6 N. Y. Ave.\nN.W.. Attorney.\nSUPREME COURT OF THE DIBTRICT OF\nColumbia. Holding Probate Court\u2014No.\n40899. Administration \u2014This is to give no\ntice that the subscriber, of the District of\nHolumbia. has obtained from the Pioba'e\nourt of the District of Columbia, letters\ntestamentary on the estate o, Morris\nLuchs. late of the District of Columbia, de\nceased. Al! persons having claims a.ainst\nthe deceased are hereby warned lot exliipit\nthe same, with the vouchers thereoi, legally\nauthenticated, to the subsenoer. on or be\nfore the 20th day of November. A.D. 1931.\notherwise they may by law be excluded from\nall benefit ol said estate. Given under my\nhand this 20th day of November. 1930.\nBETTY B LUCHS. 3300 Mass. ave. n.w.\nSeal.) Attest: THEODORE COGSWELL.\nRegister of Wilis for the District of Colum\nbta. Clerk ol the Probate Court.\nCELL A CCU. Attorneys.\n\u25a0UPREME COURT OF THE DISTRICT OF\nColumbia, holding Probate Court\u2014No.\n40940. Administration \u2014This is to give no\ntice that the subscribers, ol the District\nof Columbia, have obtained from the Pro\nbate Court of the District oi Columbia,\nletters testamentary on the estate of Rosalie\nSmith, late of the District o? Columbia,\ndeceased. All persons having claims against\ntIW deceased are hereby warned to exhibit\nlb same, with the vouchers thereof, legally\nauthenticated, to the subscribers, on or be\nfore the 10th day of November. AD 1931;\notVierwise they may by law be excluded from\nan benefit of said estate Given ur.der our\nbands this 10th day of November. 1930.\nJOHN M. SMITH. WALTER 8. SMITH.\nAttest: -Seal THEODORE COGSWELL*\nRegister of Wills for the District of Colum\nbia. Clerk of the Probate Court.\nn 022 29-de\u00ab\nGEORGE C. GERTMAN. Attorney.\nIN THE SUPREME COURT OF THE Dis\ntrict of Columbia \u2014Charles E. Henderson,\net al.. Trustees Plaintiffs, vs William S.\nPro'll, et al Defendants Equity No. 51825\n\u2014Order of Publication\u2014The obiect cf this\nauit is to obtain a decree lor the sale or\ncertain real estate under a charitable trust\nby a trustee to be appointed for that pur\npose and for reinvestment of the proceeds.\nUpon motion of the plaintiffs it is. by the\ncourt, this 2\u00abth day of November. A D 1930.\nordered that the defendants, William 8\nPrb'tt. Lucv B Prout. Laura L. Prout. Mary\n<J Prout. Mar* G Peter. Julia P Anderson.\nThomas Vinson. Nannie 8 Vinson. Annie S\nVinson. Jonathan S Prout. Harriet C. Bar\ntow. Clarence M. Oddie. Grace Oddie. Sarah\nB Oddie, Ta ke,- L. Oddie. Anna O Siebert.\nJames S Davidscn. Mary O Davidson, indi\nvidually and as trustee: Ellen D. Thomas.\nJohn H Davidson. Heath D Davidson.\nThomas B Davidson. Rebecca D. Dav.dson.\nSat ah Field. Laura Griffith. Henry Bradley.\nOeorae C Bradlev. Mm R Bradley. Jane\nB Bradley. Mary B Anderson Mane Txiutse\nArmstrong Davidson. H Bradley Davidson.\nJr.. and Richard Porter Davidson cause their\nappearance to be entered herein on or before\n\u2022he fortieth day exclusive of Sundays and\nlegal holiday*, after the day of the first pub\nlication hereof, otherwise this cause will be\ntaken as confessed, and that the defendants.\nth\u00bb unknown heirs, alienees and devisees of\nWilliam Prout. William Prout. Jr.: Martha\nH McKnight. Ellen 8 Oddie. George S. Brad\nley. John Davis. Sarah Davis. Henry Brad\nlev and Mary Bradley, cause their appear\nance to be entered herein on or before the\nfirst rule d*y occurring one month after the\nday of the first publication hereof, other\nwise as to them this cause will be taken as\nconfessed, provided a opy hereof be pub-\nBched once a week for three successive weeks\nin the Washington Law Reporter and The\nEvening Star, longer and other publications\nbeing dispensed with for satisfactory cause\nshown by the bill of complaint. JENNINGS\nBAILEY. Justice \u2018Seal.) A true copy. Test:\nPRANK E CUNNINGHAM, Clerk By HARRY\nM HULL. Aaat. Cloir no29.deg 13 _\nRESORTS.\nATLANTIC CITY, N. J.\n$230 EUROPEAN m\nsteamships\u201d\nAu*mAUA\nHONOLULU. NEW I ALAND\nJ The Well Equipped Royal Mall Steamers\ni \"AORANGI/; Jan. 3. March 4. April 29\n\u2022\u2022NIAGARA, Feb. 4. Apr. 1. May 23\nSail from Vancouver. B. C.\nPer fare, etc apply Can Pac. Rwy. 14th\n\u25a0t at New York Ave. NW Washington, oi\nto the Canadian Australasian Line, 999 West\nS\u00bb-,unn St Vao\u00ab\u00a9pv*i, b. C.\n1\nRADIO FANS WAIT\nLAMONT PROGRAM\nAdministration Plans for Re-\nlief of Jobless to Be Dis- i\ncussed by Leader.\nSecretary cf Commerce Robert P. La-\nmc,nt, speaker tonight in the National j\nRadio Forum arranged by The Wash- J\nington Star and broadcast by WMAL\nand a coast-to-coast network of Co\nlumbia Broadcasting System stations,\nwill give a comprehensive review of\nsteps taken by the Government in co\noperation v.ith the States to alleviate\nunemployment and business depression.\nSecretary Lamon\u2019t talk will be a re\ncapitulation of the efforts made by the\nadministration and others to provide\nwork for the nation\u2019s jobless and re\nstore the stability of business. At the\ntime of the broadcast he will be in\nChicago attending a banquet, but spe\ncial arrangements have been made to\npick up the talk from a private room\nin the hotel where the banquet will\nbe given.\nWMAL also will broadcast a talk\nduring the Chronicles period by Lieut.\nJohn McCloy. U. S. N.. retired, and\none of the few men to receive the\nCongressional Medal of Honor for ex-\ntraordinary valor on the high seas\ntwice within a lifetime. He will relate\nhis experiences from the Boxer upris- i\ning to Vera Cruz, where he acted as\na human decoy to draw the fire of\nMexican guns.\nThriller Is Listed.\nThe Hank Simmons Show Boat pro\nduction, which will follow the radio\nforum, as usual, will be a four-act\nthriller, \"The Maid of the Mill.\u201d The\nstory concerns the endeavors of a mo\nnopolist to gain control of certain mill\ninterests.\nRosamund Johnson and a chorus of\nspiritual singers will present a program\nof 10 Southern melodies in the Dixie\nEchoes period. Among them are \u201cRoll,\nJordan, Roll,\u201d \u201cWhere Shall I Go?\" and\n\u201cSomebody Got Lost in de Storm.\u201d\nThe Round Towners\u2019 Quartet and\nFreddie Rich's Orchestra will provide\nthe program called \u201cDancing Yester\ndays.\u201d Popular melodies will be fea\ntured.\nWRC and other National Broadcast\ning Co. stations will broadcast tonight\na program marking the 100th anni\nversary celebration of the founding of\nthe hydrographic office cf the Navy.\nSecretary of Navy Adams pill be the\nspeaker. Music will be provided by the\nNavy Band.\nDamrosch Picks March.\nThe inarch from Raffs \u201cLenore\u201d\nslnphony will be featured by Walter\nDamrosch and his symphony orches- I\nt\u2019Ta in the Electric Hour. The other j\nflections include Rachmaninoffs \u201cPre-\nRide in C Sharp Minor.\u201d Beethoven's\n\u201cPolonaise for Strings\u201d and the \"Morn- i\ning Paper Waltz\u201d by Strauss.\nHarold Veo and his orchestra make\ntheir debut in the Wilkins program, j\nRudolph Schramm also will apprar as\nthe new conductor of the gas company\nensemble, to be heard from 6:15 to 6:45\no'clock. He has arranged a varied pro\ngram, which includes \"Bunch of\nRoses,\u201d \u201cOnly a Rose\" and \u201cThe Whis\ntler and His Dog.\u201d\nGretta Ludwig, contralto, and Big\nEd. harmonica virtuoso, will contribute\nto the program of WJSV. The station\nalso will broadcast a number of other\nfeatures, one of which is the weekly\nSunday school lesson.\nA concert by the Kohala Melody Boys\ni and a recital by Rese Sokol, soprano,\nare high lights of WOL\u2019s musical pro\ngram.\nCHICAGO STATIONS\nASSAIL RADIO LAWS\nFederal Commission\u2019s Eight of\nBegulation Challenged as In\nvasion of Their Property.\nBy the Associated Press.\nThe validity cf the radio act of 1927,\nunder which the Federal Radio Com\nmission was authorized to regulate\np broadcasting, was assailed yesterday in\nthe Supreme Court.\nIt was contended by three Chicago\ni stations\u2014W\u00dfCW. WMBB and WOK\u2014\nthat Congress in the exercise of its\ncontrol over interstate commerce had\nexceeded its powers when it authorized\nthe commission to refuse to renew li\ncenses without providing compensation.\nUnder commission orders WRCW was\nrequired to reduce its power and the\nother two stations were driven off the\nair. Counsel for owners argued that\nthese orders constituted taking their\nproperty without due process of law.\nWhile they did not challenge Federal\ncontrol over radio, they insisted that\nthe law was invalid because they were\nbeing deprived of property rights with\nout compensation.\nSolicitor General Thacher Insisted\nthat the radio act was a proper regu\nlation of interstate traffic, as clearly\nwithin the Jurisdiction of Congress as\nthe regulation of any other type oi\ninterstate commerce. He denied that\n1 any one obtained a property right to\nthe ether by prior appropriation, and\nsaid the cases presented no basis for\nJ the contention that the Government\nwas taking property from the owners\nof the station. He insisted that the\nact was a necessary exercise of Federal\nauthority to make broadcasting possi\nble. declaring that without such regu\nlation chaotic conditions would result\ni which the Federal Government would\nf be powerless to remedy.\nMajor \u201cChain\u201d Features\n\nCOMING INTO WASHINGTON.\ni 7:30 \u2014One hundredth anniversary of\nhydrographic office of the Navy;\naddress by Secretary of Navy\nI Adams, and music by Navy\nBand\u2014W\u00dfC and N. B. C. net\nj work.\n9:oo\u2014Electric Hour; Damrosch Sym\nphony Orchestra and Floyd Gib.\nbons \u2014WRC and N. B. C. net\ni work.\n9:30 \u2014National Radio Forum; review\nof unemployment and business\ndepression by Secretary of Com\nmerce Lamont\u2014WMAL and C.\nB. S. network.\n10:00\u2014B. A. Rolfe Orchestra; dance\nmusic\u2014W\u00dfC and N. B. C. net\nwork.\ns 11:00\u2014Hank Simmons\u2019 Show Boat;\n\u201cThe Maid of the Mill,\" four\ne act melodrama\u2014WMAL and C.\nJ B. S. network.\n5 12:00 \u2014Dedication ceremonies In con\nnection with opening of new\nf studios of Station WBBM; va\nriety program\u2014WMAL and C.\nB. S. network.\nHIGHLIGHTS ELSEWHERE.\nB:oo\u2014Dramatization of circus life\u2014\nWJZ, WBAL, KDKA. KYW,\nWHAM. WBZ and WBZA.\n9:3o\u2014Master Minstrels; Male Quartet\nand Sanford\u2019s Orchestra\u2014WJZ,\nWBAL. WHAM. KDKA, WLW,\n1 WJR. KYW, WBZ and WBZA.\n10:00\u2014Chicago Civic Opera Co.; \u201cLa\nTraviaU\u201d WBAL. KDKA.\nWBZ, WBZA, WHAM and\nWIBO.\n11:00 \u2014Slumber music; Laurier String\ni Ensemble\u2014WJZ, KFAB and\nI CKGW.\n12:30\u2014Nocturne; organ recital by Ann\nLeaf WABC, WEAN and\nWNAC.\nh Flashes from The Evening Star, a\nresume of world newt, it broadcast\ndaily by WMAL at 5:45 o'clock.\nmm 1\nTHE EVENING STAR. WASHINGTON, D. 0.. SATURDAY. DEC FA I HER G. 1930.\nToday on the Radio\n(All time p.m., unless otherwise indicated.)\n11 MAI 475 9 Meters\nW IUAIj 630 Kilocycles.\nI:4s\u2014Penn-Navy foot ball game.\n4:30 \u2014Foot Ball Souvenir program.\nI 4:4s\u2014Notre Dame University of\nSouthern California foot ball\ngame.\n5:45 \u2014Flashes from The Evening Star,\nj 6:00 \u2014Correct time.\n6:01 \u2014Resumption of Notre Dame-\nUniversity of Southern Cali\n-1 fornia foot ball game.\n7:15 \u2014\u201cThe Romance of American\nIndustry,\u201d by Walker D. Hines.\n7:30 \u2014Chronicles.\n8:00 \u2014Correct time.\n8:01 \u2014Dixie Echoes.\nB:3o \u2014Dancing yesterdays.\n8:45 \u2014The Silversmiths.\n9:00 \u2014Herb Gordon's Orchestra.\n9:30 \u2014National Radio Forum; speaker,\nSecretary of Commerce Lamont.\n10:00 \u2014Hank Simmons\u2019 Show Boat.\n11:00 \u2014Mount Royal Orchestra.\n11:30 \u2014Guy Lombardo and His Royal\nCanadians.\n12:00\u2014Correct time.\n12:01 to I:oo\u2014Dedication ceremonies\nin connection with opening oi\nWBBM.\nYY'f'kj 228.9 Meters.\nn ULI 1,310 Kilocycles.\n3:30 \u2014Good afternoon program.\n3:45 \u2014\u201cYour Astrologic Chart,\u201d by Vir\nginia T. Dawson.\n4:oo\u2014Dance music.\n1 4 30\u2014Dvorak's \"Quartet in F Major.\u201d\ni 5:00 \u2014Mod.rn Nights.\n5:30 \u2014One-time Opportunities.\n6:00 \u2014Studio feature.\n6:05 \u2014Sambo and Ed.\n6:ls\u2014Program by Walter T. Holt.\n6:45 \u2014Kohala Melody Boys.\n7:00 \u2014Rose Sokol, soprano.\n7:20 \u2014News flashes.\n8:00 \u2014Announcement of the verdict of\n\u201cThe Trial of Vivienne Ware.\"\nDIRECT U. S.-CHINA\nWIRELESS IS OPENED\nExchange of Greetings Between\nHoover and Chiang Inaugurates\nCommercial Service.\nBx the Associated Press.\nSHANGHAI, December 6.\u2014Direct\ncommercial wireless service between\nChina and the United States was in\naugurated here today with an exchange\nof congratulatory messages between\nj President Chiang Kai-Shek and Presi\nj dent Hoover.\nOpening of the Nationalist govern\nment's new radio station here to com\nj mercial business provided the necessary\nlink in the Orient. The new station\nbrings China into direct communica\ntion with other stations throughout the\nOrient as well as with the Western\nHemisphere.\nThe new station consists of high\npowered short-wave apparatus, which\nfor communication with the Americas\nwill work principally with the Radio\nCorporation of America station in San\nFrancisco.\nThe Shanghai station will work with\nother Oriental links and with radio\nplants in Paris and Berlin to com\nmunicate v.ith areas west of here.\nA large number of Nationalist gov\nernment officials participated in the\nopening ceremonies. All asserted the\ninauguration of the service marked the\nbeginning of a new era in China's\nrelationship with Western nations.\nSpeakers said the new channel of\ncommunication would bring China\ncloser to the Western nations through a\ngreater exchange of ideas. Heretofore\nthe only wireless channel to the United\nStates was through a relay at Manila.\nLIDO CLUB WILL GIVE\nDINNER DANCE TONIGHT\nElaborate Entertainment Program\nArranged for Annual Gathering\nat Carlton Hotel.\nThe annual dinner dance of the\nLido Civic Club of Washington will\nbe held in the Carlton Hotel at 8:30\no\u2019clock tonight. Guests of honor will\ninclude United States Attorney Leo A.\nRover and Mrs. Rover, Representative\nand Mrs. E. W. Goss of Connecticut\nand Count Albert Marchetti di Mu-\nraglio. charge d'affaires of the Italian\nembassy.\nGregory Cipriani, president of the\nclub, will be the toastmaster. An\nelaborate program of entertainment, 1\nled by Miss Ethel West, has been ar\nranged.\nJOSEPH ASHI ELECTED\nBY DISABLED VETERANS\nAce-Rasmussen Chapter Holds An\nnual Vote\u2014New Commander\nPlans Membership Drive.\ni 1 Joseph Ashi was elected commander\nI of the Ace-Ra K mussen Chapter of the\n[j Disabled American Veterans Thursday\ni night at the annual election in the board\nroom of the District Building. Comdr.\nAshi served with the 108th Infantry of\nthe 27th Division, is a former senior\nvice commander of the chapter, and\nsucceeds Frank M. Owens. The other\nofficers elected were: Edward Earle,\nformerly of the Navy, senior vice com\nmander; Charles Ruby, D. S. C., former\nly of the 16th Infantry, junior vice\ncommander, and Earl G. Hendrick,\nformerly o fthe 10th Field Artillery, as\nadjutant and treasurer. The A new\nExecutive Committee will be composed\nof Richard Melton, Herbert Church,\nF. M. Owens, Lee Turner and E. C.\nBabcock.\nAt the annual convention of the Dis\ntrict of Columbia department of the\nD. A. V. on January 17. at the Raleigh\nHotel, Ace-Rasmussen Chapter, due to\nits membership, will have more votes\nthan any other chapter in Washington,\nand it Ls the intention of Comdr. Ashi\nimmediately to launch a membership\ndrive in order to increase the repre\nsentation Irom the chapter at the na\ntional convention, which will be held in\nWilkes-Barre next June.\nIOWA SOCIETY IS HOST\nWill Honor Legislators Tonight\nWith Reception and Ball.\nThe lowa Society of Washington\nwill open its season with a reception\nand ball at the Willard Hotel at 8:30\no\u2019clock this evening.\nClaude Porter, interstate commerce\ncommissioner and president of the so\nciety, has planned this first meeting\nas a reception to the lowa congres\nsional delegation and a \u201cget-together\u201d\nfor all lowans\nThere will be dancing and cards.\nCADET IS APPOINTED\ni\nC. J. Hoy Gets President\u2019s Place at\nWest Point.\nCharles J. Hoy, 3000 Tilden street,\ni private, Battery E, 260th Coast Artil\n-1 lery, District of Columbia National\nGuard, has been appointed by the\nPresident a cadet at large at the West\nPoint Military Academy, subject to\nqualification at the entrance examina\ntion, March 3, 1931.\nI L\nIX\u2019FH\u2019 315.6 Meters.\n950 Kilocycles.\nI:4s\u2014Penn-Navy foot ball g?me.\n4:3o\u2014The Marionettes.\n4:45 \u2014The Merrymakers.\n5:00 \u2014Whyte's Orchestra.\n5:30 \u2014The Blip Acres.\n5:59 \u2014Correct time.\n6:00 \u2014News flashes.\n6:lo\u2014Saltzman\u2019s Orchestra.\n6:ls\u2014Breeskin Concert Quintet.\n7:00 \u2014Amos \u2019n\u2019 Andy.\n7:ls\u2014The Jesters.\n7:30 \u2014Address by Secretary of Navy\nAdams at the 100th Anniversary\nCel:bration of the Hydrographic\nOffice of the Navy.\nB:oo\u2014Wilkins Orchestra.\nB:3o\u2014The Silver Flute.\n9:oo\u2014Damrosch Symphony Orchestra.\n10:00\u2014B. A. Rolfo Orchestra.\n11:00 \u2014Weather forecast.\n11:01\u2014Shoreham Orchestra.\n12:00 to I:oo\u2014Rudy Vallee Orchestra.!\niWTIfiV 205.4 Meters.\nJ 1,460 Kilocycles.\n2:oo\u2014Aft:rnoon musicale.\ni 2:30 \u2014Art Stone, pianist.\n3:00 \u2014Ryder Violin Ensemble.\n,3:30 \u2014Mother Gcose party.\n4:oo\u2014\u2019Triart Trio.\ns:oo\u2014Science and History.\n5:15 \u2014Studio feature.\ns:4s\u2014\u201cCongress of Today.\u201d\n6:oo\u2014News flashes.\n6:12\u20140n the Mat.\n6:ls\u2014Classified program.\n6:4s\u2014Police bulletins.\n7:oo\u2014Dinner music.\n7:17 \u2014T Fpbone flash.\n7:l\u00df\u2014\u201cWhither Away.\u201d\n7:3o\u2014Time signal.\n7:31 \u2014Two-Eleven.\n8:00\u2014\u201cFront Line Politics.\u201d\nB:ls\u2014Harmonica solas by Melvin\nGower.\nB:3o\u2014Sunday school lesson.\n9:oo\u2014Pa Brown and His Brownies.\n9:3o\u2014Big Ed.\n9:4s\u2014Gretta Ludwig, contralto.\n10:00\u2014Studio program.\n10:15 to 11:00 \u2014Dance music.\nARMY ORDERS\nCol. Henry C. Bonvcastle, Quartcr-\nI master Corps, who has been under\n1 treatment at Walter Reed General Hos\npital, has been assigned to duty at Bos\nton; Capt. Edward F. French, Signal\nCorps, has been transferred from San\nFrancisco to the Panama Canal Zone;\nCapt. Butler L. Knight, Infantry, from\nFort Sam Houston. Tex., to St. Louis,\nMo.; Capt. George E. Thompson. Quar\ntermaster Corps, from Philadelphia to\nHawaii; First Lieut. Russell G. Duff,\nField Artillery.-from Madison Barracks,\nN. Y\u201e to Hawaii; Second Lieut. Mar\nshall H. Fay, Air Corps, from Walter\nReed General Hospital, this city, to\nMitchei Field. N. Y.; First Lieut. Dan\niel P. Buckland, Cavalry, from Chicago\nto the 10th Cavalry at Fort Huachuca,\nAriz., and First Lieut. Marcellus L.\nStockton, jr., from Fort Huachuca, Ariz.,\ntc Chicago.\nNAVY ORDERS\nLieut. Comdr. G:orge E Maynard, to\nduty as engineer officer, U. S. S. Mil\nwaukee.\nLieut. John A. McDonnell, orders Oc\ntober 6 revoked. Detached U. S. S. Flor\nida to sick leave three months.\nLieut, (junior grade) John A. Glick,\ndetached Division of Fleet Training,\nNavy Department, about December 13;\nto U. S. S. Raleigh.\nLieut, (junior grade) Alan R. Mont\ngomery, detached U. S. S. Lawrence; to\nU. S. S. Hale.\nLieut, (junior grade) Lewis S. Parks,\ndetached U. S. S. S-36; to U. S. S. S-40.\nLieut, (junior grade) James M. Rob\ninson, detached U. S. S. Fairfax about\nDecember 8; to U. S. S. Biddle.\nLieut, (junior grade) Charles J. Stark\nms, detached U. S. S. Kane about De\ncember 8: to U. S. S. Crowninshield.\nLieut, (junior grade) Richard F. Stout,\ndetached U. S. S. Kane about December\n8; to U. S. S. Richmond.\nEnsign Eugene C. Carusi, detached 17.\nS. S. Utah about December 8; to Asia\ntic Fleet.\nMedical Corps.\nComdr. Duncan C. Walton. Medical\nCorps, orders November 7 revoked; to!\ncontinue duty Navy Medical School, 1\nWashington. D. C.\nLieut. Comdr. George N. McClintock,\nMedical Corps, detached U. S. S. Lang-\nley; to U. S. S. Holland.\nSupply Corps.\nLieut. Comdr. George C. Simmons,\nSupply Corps, orders November 21 modi\nfied; to U. s. S. Pennsylvania on Jan-\nI uary 2, 1931.\nLieut. George W. Davis, Suply Corps,\nj cetached Naval Air Station. Coco Solo,\nCanal Zone; to Naval Air Station, Coco\nSolo, Canal Zone, as supply officer.\nWarrant Officers.\nChief Machinist Jchn Reber, detached\nu. S. S. Antares; to U. S. S. Vireo.\nChief Pharmacist Robert K. Mason,\ndetached Naval Hospital, League Island,\nPhiladelphia. Pa.; to Marine Corps Base\nNaval Operation Base, San Diego, Calif\u2019\nChief Pay Clerk Romaine Hathaway\ndetached U. S. S. Raleigh; to U. S S\nTexas.\nMarine Corps Orders\nCapt. Robert Blake, on or about De\ncember 15 detached Marine Base. Quan\ntico, Va.. to headquarters Marine Corps,\nWashington. D. C.\nCapt. Fred G. Patchen, detached Nic\naraguan National Guard Detachment to\nMarine Base, Quantico, Va., via first\navailable Government conveyance\nFirst Lieut. Theodore A. Holdahl, de\ntached 2nd Brigade, Nicaragua, to Nic\naraguan National Guard Detachment.\nFirst Lieut. George L. Hollett, de\ntached 2nd Brigade. Nicaragua, to Ma\nrince Base, 2nd Brigade, Coco Solo,\nCanal Zone.\nDUELER NOT APPEASED\nBlood Drawn, but This Does Not\nSatisfy Victor.\nLISBON, December 6 (A>). \u2014A duel\ndrew blood here yesterday, but even\nthen did not settle the argument.\nThe principals were a son of Count\nMafra and Manuel Palma, a banker of\nAlemtejo Province. Two shots were\nexchanged, one hitting Palma in the\narm, but his antagonist refused to be\ncome reconciled, declaring his honor\nhad been wounded beyond redress,\n|l> l||||l\"l|||||l\u00bb||||||i|||||||<i|||||||\nSunday\nDinner 1\n=r Served from 12 to 10 J=\nPomona 60cl\n|p 1307 E St. n s\n1 Earle *7Ccl\n13th E St*. S M *7\n||JW\\\" yiiiu\nET Home* of 1\nDinner* ~r~\nr.illlllillllliiiHlliilHlillllliilllliillllig\nDANCING.\nCITY CLUB DANCES.\nTI\u2019ES.-THURS.-SAT., P.M.\u2014.VOr. 7.V.\n1 MAIN BAI.I. R00M.1321) G ST. 1C\nL\u2019EGARE STUDIO\nt Specializing in ball room dancing, c m\nful attention given to beginners. Prima:\nsteps: 5 private lessons. IS. Class Tuesday.\nInstruction 8, practice 9 to 11.\n\u00a3i)3i P f\u00bbL N.W. Dec. 26)8.\nNEW ME FOUND l\nTO SEND PICTURES\nYouthful Inventor Discovers\nWay to Transmit Television\non Few Frequencies.\nBy the Associated Press.\nSAN FRANCISCO. December 6.\nPhilo T. Farnsworth, youthful inventor\nof San Francisco, today announced he\nhad discovered away of transmitting\nimages on a narrow band of radio\nfrequencies. Farnsworth said his dis\ncovery would multiply by about 40 the\nnumber of channels available for broad\ncasting television pictures.\nThis announcement was supplemented\niby his statement that the principle\nwould make possible the use of the new\nprocess for telephotoing pictures on\nthe same wires for the transmission of\nnews by applying inexpensive attach\nments to the teletype printers now gen\nerally utilized.\nRevolutionary Discovery.\nFarnsworth's scheme to narrow a\ntelevision w'ave band to a range of three\nto six kilocycles is his second revolu\ntionary \u00a3\u00abvelopment in this field in\nrecent months. In his first he suc\nceeded in doing away with the scanning\ndisc and in transmitting without ma\nchinery or any moving parts. Using\nspecially designed vacuum tubes for\nboth sending and receiving, he was\nable to send motion pictures containing\n640,000 elements of light times a\nsecond. \u201cStills\u201d he transmitted at the\nrate of 20 pictures a second, containing\n40.000 light elements, which is equiva- j\nlent to ipore than five times the detail\nof the ordinary newspaper picture.\nSixteen pictures a second are all that j\nare necessary to give the eye the im\npression of continuous motion on the\nscreen.\nLeft Much to Be Desired.\nFarnsworth\u2019s first experimenting in\nthis field was with ultra-short waves\non a wide band of frequencies and\ntherefore its meaning in a practical j\nway left much to be desired, for there I\nwould not be more than one or two!\nchannels available on such a wide j\nrange for general breadcasting and it\nwould take pictures, with sound ac\ncompaniment, into only those homes\ni having short wave receivers.\nBy narrowing down the band, Farns\nworth said he was able to transmit\nimages on standard wavelengths and\nthe receiving apparatus could be at\ntached to the ordinary radio receiver,\nalthough future developments presage\nthe manufacture of a radio in which\nI the picture receiver is built into the\ncabinet.\nTODAY'S AMUSEMENTS.\nShubert-Belasco \u2014Grace George in\n\u201cThe First Mrs. Fraser,\u201d at 2;30 and\n8:30 p.m.\nNational\u2014\" The Apple Cart,\u201d at 2:20\nand 8:20 p.m.\nGayety\u2014\u201cSugar Babies,\u201d at 2:15 and\n8:15 p.m.\nMetropolitan \u201cMother\u2019s Cry.\u201d at\n11:15 am., 1, 2:45, 4:30, 6:15, 8 and\n9:45 p m.\nFox\u2014\u201cLightnin\u2019,\u201d at 11:30 a.m., 2:07, I\n4:36, 7:14 and 9:40 p.m.\nColumbia\u2014\u201c Feet First,\u201d at 11 am., i\n1:05, 3:10, 5:15, 7:20 and 9:30 p.m. j\nRialto\u2014\"Today,\u201d at 11:40 a.m., 1:40.\n3:40, 5:40, 7:40 and 9:40 p.m.\nPalace \u2014\u201cThe Bat Whispers,\u201d at 12,\n2:16, 4:37, 7:23 and 9:44 p.m.\nEarle \u2014\u201cThe Widow from Chicago,\u201d\nat 12:04, 2:23, 4:42, 7:45 and 10:04 p.m.\nR-K-O Keith\u2019s\u2014\u201c Big Money,\u201d at!\n11:29 am., 1:31, 3:33, 5:33, 7:35 and:\n9:37 p.m.\nAmbassador \u201cCheck and Double\nCheck,\u201d at 6:15, 8 and 9:55 p.m.\nCentral \u2014\u201cUp the River,\u201d 11 a.m. to\n11 pm.\nTivoli\u2014\u201cBillv the Kid,\u201d at 1:45, 3r50,\n6, 7:45 and 9:10 p.m.\nTl T\"? CALENDARS\nDIARIES\nJl. -ji JLrnm NOW HERE\nStore Hours\u2014B to 5:30\nE. Morri